name: Coastal Trail
column4: The Tony Knowles Coastal Trail runs south from the railroad depot downtown by the Ted Steven's International Airport and ends in the world renown cross country ski park, Kincaid park. Earthquake Park

name: Sullivan Nature Trail
column4: An urban handicap accessible trail to contemplate life and take a break from the roads.

name: Campbell Creek Trail
column4: Runs from Diamond High School, around Taku lake, and access to UAA/APU. Great commuter trail.

name: Campbell Creek Trail
column4: Runs from Diamond High School, around Taku lake, and access to UAA/APU. Great commuter trail.

name: Ship Creek Trail
column4: This trail runs next to Anchorage's urban salmon run. The trail begins at the railroad depot and ends right before the high-tech Hernandez fish hatchery.  Caution: treking or fishing outisde the eastern bound of the trail trespasses on to the Fort Richardson army base.

name: Little Omalley
column4: A comfortable hike until you cross the south tributary of Campbell creek. Muddy in spring and after a strong rain. Climbing Little O'Malley is technically easy but strenuous. Photosphere!

name: Anchorage Overlook
column4: With easy access to parking, this is the best public view of Anchorage in town without climbing a mountain.

name: Rabbit Lake
column4: This trail has difficult parking that is both steep and bumpy. The trail is mostly flat after a first hour and comfortable to do with the family. Photosphere!

name: Wolverine Peak
column4: This trail starts though cottonwood trees and crosses over a creek bridge to start up hill all the way through many different ecological and geologic zones to reach the top of this quintessential Anchorage hike.

name: Monitor Well Road / Winter Horse Trail
